# TypeScript Security Guidelines

Applied when working with TypeScript source files. Use Australian English spelling throughout.

---

## Input Validation

- Validate all external input at boundaries using Zod (or equivalent): HTTP bodies, query params, message queue payloads, config, environment variables
- Infer TypeScript types from Zod schemas — do not duplicate type definitions manually
- Use `parse()` for hard failures at the boundary; `safeParse()` when you need to handle errors and continue
- Apply length limits, format constraints, and range checks to all string and numeric inputs
- Do not trust data arriving from a queue, file system, or webhook any less than HTTP input

---

## Type Safety as Security

- Avoid `as` type assertions on untrusted data — they bypass the type checker without runtime checks
- Use `unknown` instead of `any` for untyped input; narrow explicitly with type guards or Zod
- Use branded types for domain primitives (IDs, emails, currencies) to prevent accidental mixing
- Enable `noUncheckedIndexedAccess` — prevents silent `undefined` from array/object access

---

## Authentication and Authorisation

- Validate JWT claims: `iss`, `aud`, `exp`, `nbf` — reject tokens missing any claim
- Use short-lived access tokens (≤15 min) with refresh token rotation
- Never compare tokens or hashes with `===` — use `crypto.timingSafeEqual()` to prevent timing attacks
- Implement authorisation checks after authentication; check at the use-case boundary, not only at the route level

---

## Secrets Hygiene

- Never hardcode secrets in source — use environment variables; validate with Zod at startup
- Never log secrets, tokens, or full request bodies containing credentials
- Rotate secrets on suspected exposure; treat rotation as a normal operational procedure
- Use `.env.example` to document required variables; add `.env` to `.gitignore`

---

## Dependency Security

- Run `npm audit --audit-level=high` in CI as a blocking step
- Review transitive dependency updates; use `npm ci` (not `npm install`) in CI for reproducible installs
- Scan for supply-chain risks with `socket` or `snyk` for high-value projects
- Remove unused packages (`npx depcheck`); smaller surface area means fewer vulnerabilities

---

## Checklist

- [ ] All external input validated with Zod at every boundary
- [ ] No `as` assertions on untrusted data; `unknown` used and narrowed
- [ ] JWT claims (`iss`, `aud`, `exp`) validated on every token
- [ ] Secrets validated at startup; never logged
- [ ] `npm audit --audit-level=high` passes in CI
- [ ] Stack traces never returned in API error responses
